   ]
  },
  {

   "source": [
    "[![Binder](https://mybinder.org/badge_logo.svg)](https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/UCL-EO/Workshop2022/HEAD?labpath=notebooks%2F005_Solar_Practical.ipynb)"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## Introduction"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Two critical driving variables we will need to understand patterns and responses of terrestrial vegetation are the incident shortwave solar radiation and temperature at the land surface. In this practical, we will explore the variations in shortwave solar radiation as a function of latitude and time of year, and associate surface temperature with these. \n",
    "\n",
    "In a future exercise, we will use such data to drive a model of carbon dynamics by vegetation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2018-02-19T19:44:28.515828Z",
     "start_time": "2018-02-19T19:44:28.504855Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from python.solar import solar_model,radiation\n",
    "import scipy.ndimage.filters\n",
    "from python.cru import getCRU,splurge\n",
    "from datetime import datetime, timedelta\n",
    "# import codes we need into the notebook"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Incident PAR"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Solar radiation drives the Earth system and strongly impacts the terrestrial Carbon cylcle. \n",
    "\n",
    "We will use a model of solar radiation to examine diurnal and seasonal variations. We use the [PyEphem](http://rhodesmill.org/pyephem/) Python package, which allows us to calculate the position of the sun with respect to an observer on Earth. So we need time as well as longitude and latitude.\n",
    "\n",
    "Before we do that, let's make sure we understand the main factors causing these variations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will use the `solar_model` method that gives time axis in units of Julian days, as well as the solar zenith angle (in degrees), the Earth-Sun distance, as well as the solar radiation in mol(photons)/m^2s.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Help on function solar_model in module python.solar:\n",
      "\n",
      "solar_model(secs, mins, hours, days, months, years, lats, longs, julian_offset='2000/1/1')\n",
      "    A function that calculates the solar zenith angle (sza, in\n",
      "    degrees), the Earth-Sun distance (in AU), and the instantaneous \n",
      "    downwelling solar radiation in mol(photons) per square meter per\n",
      "    second for a set of time(s) and geographical locations.\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "help(solar_model)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A small aside on defining dates. We will be defining the date by the day of year (`doy`) when we run these exercises, but the code we are using requires a definition of date as days and month. To convert between these in Python, we use the `datetime` module to specify the 1st of January for the given year in the variable `datetime_object`, then add on the `doy` (actually `doy-1` because when `doy` is 1 we mean January 1st). We then specify `day` `month` and `year` as `datetime_object.day`,`datetime_object.month`,`datetime_object.year`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 3,

   ],
   "source": [
    "# set a date by year and doy\n",
    "year = 2020\n",
    "doy = 32\n",
    "\n",
    "# convert to datetime object\n",
    "datetime_object = datetime(year,1,1)+timedelta(doy-1)\n",
    "# extract day, month and year\n",
    "datetime_object.day,datetime_object.month,datetime_object.year"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Orbital mechanics impose a variation in the Earth-Sun distance over the year. This is typically expressed in [Astronomical Units](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomical_unit) (AU), so relative to the mean Earth-Sun distance.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Exo-atmospheric solar radiation E0 ($W/m^2$) (total shortwave radiation) is defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "E0 = \\frac{G_{sc}}{r^2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $G_{sc}$ is the Solar Constant (around 1361 $W/m^2$) and $r$ is the Earth-Sun distance in AU (inverse-squared law). \n",
    "\n",
    "Around half of the SW energy is in the PAR region, so to calculate PAR, we scale by 0.5. \n",
    "\n",
    "The energy content of PAR quanta is around $220.e-3$  $MJmol^{-1}$, so the top of atmosphere (TOA) PAR solar radiation is $\\frac{E0}{2 \\times 220.e-3}$ $mol/{m^2s}$, so 3093 = $mol/{m^2s}$ at 1 AU.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can use `solar_model` to calculate this distance and ipar variation, and visualise the orbit:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false

     ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The seasons\n",
    "\n",
    "We need to take account of this annual (7%) variation when we model PAR interception by vegetation, but it is not the strongest cause of variation over the year. Solar radiation is projected onto the Earth surface. We can express this projection by the cosine of the solar zenith angle. When the Sun is directly overhead (zenith angle zero degrees), then the projection is 1. As the zenith angle increases, the projected radiation decreases until it is 0 at a zenith angle of 90 degrees.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The seasons are not directly related to the Earth-Sun distance variations then. They arise in the main because the Earth is tilted on its axis by 23.5 degrees (obliquity).\n",
    "\n",
    "![](https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/thumbnails/image/axis_.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will use `solar_model`  to calculate the amount of incoming PAR. To do this, we assume:\n",
    "\n",
    "* that PAR is around 50% of total downwelling (shortwave) radiation,\n",
    "* that the optical thickness ($\\tau$) of the atmosphere in the PAR region is around 0.2\n",
    "* and that we multiply by all this by $\\cos(sza)$ to project on to a flat surface.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's look at how that varies over the year, for some different latitudes."
   ]
  },

    "## Weather generation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To run our photosynthesis model, we need to know the temperature as well as the IPAR. That is rather complicated to model, so we will use observational data to drive the model. We choose the interpolated [CRU climate dataset](https://sites.uea.ac.uk/cru/data) for this. \n",
    "\n",
    "You can select this using the [`getCRU()`](python/cru.py) function for a given latitude, longitude and year (2011 to 2019 inclusive here). This gives you access to **monthly** minimum and maximum temperatures, `f['tmn']` and `f['tmx']` respectively, as well as cloud cover percentage `f['cld']`. The dataset is for the land surface only. If you specify somewhere in the ocean, you will get an interpolated result.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Scaling iPAR by cloud cover\n",
    "\n",
    "We will use the cloud percentage to reduce iPAR, by setting a reduction factor by 1/3 (to a value of 2/3) on cloudy days (when `f['cld']` is 100) and 1 when there is no cloud.\n",
    "\n",
    "    scale = 1 - f['cld']/300"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

    "from python.cru import getCRU\n",
    "\n",
    "f = getCRU(2019,longitude=0,latitude=56)\n",

   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Synthesizing diurnal temperature\n",
    "\n",
    "Since we only have monthly minimum and maximum temperature, we need to be able to estimate the diurnal variation of temperature from these. We can broadly achieve this by scaling by normalised IPAR. However, there will be a time lag between greater radiation input and temperature caused by inertia in the system. We can mimic this effect with a one-sided smoothing filter that 'smears' the temperature forward in time. The degree of smearing is controlled by the filter width parameter `f` (e.g. 8 hours). This is achieved in the function `splurge`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def splurge(ipar,f=8.0,plot=False):\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    Spread the quantity ipar forward in time\n",
    "    using a 1-sided exponential filter of width \n",
    "    f * 2.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Arguments:\n",
    "        ipar: array of 1/2 hourly time step ipar values \n",
    "              (length 48)\n",
    "              \n",
    "    Keyword:\n",
    "        f : filter characteristic width. Filter is\n",
    "            exp(-x/(f*2))\n",
    "            \n",
    "    Return:\n",
    "        ipar_ : normalised, splurged ipar array\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    if f == 0:\n",
    "        return (ipar-ipar.min())/(ipar.max()-ipar.min())\n",
    "    # build filter over large extent\n",
    "    nrf_x_large = np.arange(-100,100)\n",
    "    # filter function f * 2 as f is in hours\n",
    "    # but data in 1/2 hour steps\n",
    "    nrf_large = np.exp(-nrf_x_large/(f*2))    \n",
    "    # 1-sided filter\n",
    "    nrf_large[nrf_x_large<0] = 0\n",
    "    nrf_large /= nrf_large.sum()\n",
    "    ipar_ = scipy.ndimage.filters.convolve1d(ipar, nrf_large,mode='wrap')\n",
    "    if plot:\n",
    "        plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))\n",
    "        plt.plot(nrf_x_large,nrf_large)\n",
    "    return (ipar_-ipar_.min())/(ipar_.max()-ipar_.min())\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   "source": [
    "# Calculate solar position over a day, every 30 mins\n",
    "year=2020\n",
    "doy =80\n",
    "latitude, longitude = 51,0\n",
    "dt = datetime(year,1,1) + timedelta(doy-1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# solar radiation\n",
    "jd, sza, distance, solar_radiation = solar_model(\n",
    "    0.,np.array([0.,30.]),np.arange(0,24),dt.day,dt.month,dt.year,\n",
    "    latitude, longitude)\n",
    "\n",
    "hour = (jd-jd[0])*24 \n",
    "# cosine\n",
    "mu = np.cos(np.deg2rad(sza))\n",
    "ipar = solar_radiation* parprop * np.exp(-tau/mu) * mu\n",
    "\n",
    "# show filter\n",
    "_=splurge(ipar,f=8,plot=True)"
   ]

   "source": [
    "# smear ipar\n",
    "# filter length f (hours)\n",
    "f = 1.0 # hours \n",
    "for f in np.arange(0,8):\n",
    "    ipar_ = splurge(ipar,f=f)\n",
    "    plt.plot(hour,ipar_)\n",
    "    print(f'f={f}, peak time shifted from {hour[np.argmax(ipar)]:.1f} hrs to {hour[np.argmax(ipar_)]:.1f} hrs')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A value of `f` of `8` give a 2 hour delay in the peak of around 2 hours which is a reasonable average value we can use to mimic temperature variations. A simple model of diurnal temperature variatioins then is to simply scale this by the monthly temperature minimum and maximum values:\n",
    "\n",
    "    Tc = ipar_*(Tmax-Tmin)+Tmin\n",
    "    \n",
    "One problem with this approach is that the variation we achieve in temperature (and IPAR) is significantly less than in reality. This can reduce the apparent variation in CO2 fluxes. In practice, when modellers attempt to estimate instantaneous (or short time-integral) values from means, they insert additional random variation to match some other sets of observed statistical variation (including correlations). We ignore that here, for simplicity."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2018-02-19T19:44:35.885011Z",
     "start_time": "2018-02-19T19:44:32.423569Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from datetime import datetime\n",
    "from datetime import timedelta\n",
    "\n",
    "def radiation(latitude,longitude,doy,\n",
    "              tau=0.2,parprop=0.5,year=2019,\n",
    "              Tmin=5.0,Tmax=30.0,f=8.0):\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    Simple model of solar radiation making call \n",
    "    to solar_model(), calculating modelled\n",
    "    ipar \n",
    "    \n",
    "    Arguments:\n",
    "    latitude : latitude (degrees)\n",
    "    longitude: longitude (degrees)\n",
    "    doy:  day of year (integer)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Keywords:\n",
    "    \n",
    "    tau:     optical thickness (0.2 default)\n",
    "    parprop: proportion of solar radiation in PAR\n",
    "    Tmin:    min temperature (C) 20.0 default\n",
    "    Tmax:    max temperature (C) 30.0 default\n",
    "    year:    int 2020 default\n",
    "    f:       Temperature smearing function characteristic\n",
    "             length (hours)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    # Calculate solar position over a day, every 30 mins\n",
    "    # for somewhere like London (latitude 51N, Longitude=0)\n",
    "    dt = datetime(year,1,1) + timedelta(doy-1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    jd, sza, distance, solar_radiation = solar_model(\n",
    "        0.,np.array([0.,30.]),np.arange(25),dt.day,dt.month,dt.year,\n",
    "        latitude, 0,julian_offset=f'{year}/1/1')\n",
    "    mu = np.cos(np.deg2rad(sza))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    n = mu.shape[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "    ipar = solar_radiation* parprop * np.exp(-tau/mu) * mu  # u mol(photons) / (m^2 s)\n",
    "    fd = getCRU(year,longitude=longitude,latitude=latitude)\n",
    "    Tmax = fd['tmx'][dt.month-1]\n",
    "    Tmin = fd['tmn'][dt.month-1]\n",
    "    cld = fd['cld'][dt.month-1]\n",
    "    scale = (1-cld/300.)\n",
    "    print(f'Tmin {Tmin:.2f} Tmax {Tmax:.2f} Cloud {cld:.2f} Scale {scale:.2f}')\n",
    "    # reduce irradiance by 1/3 on cloudy day\n",
    "    ipar = ipar * scale\n",
    "    # smear ipar\n",
    "    ipar_ = splurge(ipar,f=f)\n",
    "    # normalise\n",
    "    Tc = ipar_*(Tmax-Tmin)+Tmin\n",
    "    #Tc = (Tc-Tc.min())\n",
    "    #Tc = Tc/Tc.max()\n",
    "    #Tc = (Tc*(Tmax-Tmin) + (Tmin))\n",
    "    return jd-jd[0],ipar,Tc\n"
   ]
  },
